total length (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F06FF91FD39FE72FC01FDEE" author="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Patzner, R. A." box="[728,993,500,527]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" pagination="95 - 102" refId="ref50197" refString="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Patzner, R. A. (1995) A new species of Didogobius (Teleostei: Gobiidae) from the western Mediterranean. Cybium, 19, 95 - 102." type="journal article" year="1995">Ahnelt &amp; Patzner 1995</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F06FF91FF26FD9EFB3BFB93" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F06FF91FF26FD9EFBE1FD7F" blockId="51.[151,1437,500,1139]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Morphology. D VI + I,9–10; A I,9; P 13–16 (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F06FF91FD21FD9EFC29FDD2" author="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Patzner, R. A." box="[704,969,536,563]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" pagination="95 - 102" refId="ref50197" refString="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Patzner, R. A. (1995) A new species of Didogobius (Teleostei: Gobiidae) from the western Mediterranean. Cybium, 19, 95 - 102." type="journal article" year="1995">Ahnelt &amp; Patzner 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F06FF91FC34FD9FFB9FFDD3" author="Francour, P." box="[981,1151,536,563]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" pagination="139 - 141" refId="ref54559" refString="Francour, P. (2008) First records of Didogobius splechtnai along the French Mediterranean coast and additional comments about D. schlieweni. Acta Ichthyologica et Piscatoria, 38 (2), 139 - 141. https: // doi. org / 10.3750 / AIP 2008.38.2.09" type="journal article" year="2008">Francour 2008</bibRefCitation>
). Small goby with stocky body, 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F06FF91FF3DFDBAFCFEFDB7" bold="true" box="[220,798,572,598]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">large depressed head and a gently sloping snout.</emphasis>
Caudal peduncle deep, almost as deep as body. The first dorsal fin higher than the second, 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F06FF91FDFDFDE6FB52FD9B" bold="true" box="[540,1202,608,634]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">its first spine longest, giving the fin a triangular shape.</emphasis>
Caudal fin rounded. Scales visible on body from reticulate pigmentation pattern along scale edges.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F06FF91FF26FD2EFF00FCB3" blockId="51.[151,1437,500,1139]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Live coloration. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F06FF91FE61FD2EFC75FCEB" bold="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Body mostly dark brown with 3 moderately broad whitish to pale grayish bars extending onto ventral half of body, the first bar immediately in front of the first dorsal fin and extending onto ventral half of pectoral fins, plus a very thin one at the base of caudal fin</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F06FF91FC42FD76FC16FCEB" box="[931,1014,752,778]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1945,1969]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,1064,1921]" captionTargetId="figure-41@20.[151,1437,1064,1921]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 14. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Didogobius splechtnai. Photo by A. Pagano, Sicily, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601607" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601607/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). First dorsal fin colored like adjacent body, with scattered white flecks and streaks, outer membrane between first two spines white (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F06FF91FB4CFC92FADEFCCE" author="Louisy, P." box="[1197,1342,788,815]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" refId="ref60639" refString="Louisy, P. (2015) Europe and Mediterranean Marine Fish Identification Guide. 3 rd Edition. Eugen Ulmer Ed., Paris, 512 pp." type="book" year="2015">Louisy 2015</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F06FF91FAA9FC93FF33FCB3" author="Patzner, R. A." pageId="51" pageNumber="52" refId="ref62855" refString="Patzner, R. A. (2021) Gobiidae. Available from: http: // www. patzner. sbg. ac. at / Gobiidae / GobiidaeSpecies. htm (accessed 1 October 2021)" type="url" year="2021">Patzner 2021</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F06FF91FF26FCDAFD68FC96" blockId="51.[151,1437,500,1139]" box="[199,648,860,887]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F06FF91FE9EFCDAFD61FC97" authorityName="Bath" authorityYear="1971" box="[383,641,860,886]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Gammogobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="steinitzi">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F06FF91FE9EFCDAFD61FC97" box="[383,641,860,886]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Gammogobius steinitzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F06FF91FF26FC06FBB2FC03" blockId="51.[151,1437,500,1139]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Habitat. Infralittoral to circalittoral species, known from depth of 
<quantity id="2E379B383F06FF91FC7FFC06FC15FC7A" box="[926,1013,896,923]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="5.6" metricValueMin="0.4" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" unit="m" value="30.0" valueMax="56.0" valueMin="4.0">
4– 
<specimenCount id="FFC9FD543F06FF91FC5BFC06FC15FC7A" box="[954,1013,896,923]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="generic">56 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. Present in small cavities in innermost parts of large marine caves and in small bottom caves and cavities. Mostly found lying on the soft sediment in recesses, ready to dive into a nearby hole or crevice (summarized by 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F06FF91FC7CFC4FFBA6FC03" author="Francour, P." box="[925,1094,968,995]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" pagination="139 - 141" refId="ref54559" refString="Francour, P. (2008) First records of Didogobius splechtnai along the French Mediterranean coast and additional comments about D. schlieweni. Acta Ichthyologica et Piscatoria, 38 (2), 139 - 141. https: // doi. org / 10.3750 / AIP 2008.38.2.09" type="journal article" year="2008">Francour 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F06FF91FF26FC6AFB3BFB93" blockId="51.[151,1437,500,1139]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Geographic distribution. Mediterranean, there are records from the northwestern Mediterranean (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F06FF91FACCFC6AFECCFBCA" author="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Patzner, R. A." pageId="51" pageNumber="52" pagination="95 - 102" refId="ref50197" refString="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Patzner, R. A. (1995) A new species of Didogobius (Teleostei: Gobiidae) from the western Mediterranean. Cybium, 19, 95 - 102." type="journal article" year="1995">Ahnelt &amp; Patzner 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F06FF91FED6FB97FE3DFBCB" author="Francour, P." box="[311,477,1040,1067]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" pagination="139 - 141" refId="ref54559" refString="Francour, P. (2008) First records of Didogobius splechtnai along the French Mediterranean coast and additional comments about D. schlieweni. Acta Ichthyologica et Piscatoria, 38 (2), 139 - 141. https: // doi. org / 10.3750 / AIP 2008.38.2.09" type="journal article" year="2008">Francour 2008</bibRefCitation>
; 
